Raw dev notes -- From Token Hell to Reliable Smoke Tests (early-mid March 2026)

The early days of my web app API wrapper were rough. I was extracting auth tokens via
Playwright, validating them, backing them up -- and it STILL broke constantly.
This week was about stabilizing the foundation.

Key work:
- Built a comprehensive 16-endpoint smoke test script
- Persistent browser profiles replaced manual token extraction
- Added crash-resilient session refresh
- Heartbeat system with structured logging and status tracking
- Keep-alive supervisor loop as safety net
- Fixed encoding issues on Windows for logging output

The big 'aha': I was overcomplicating auth. Playwright's persistent browser profile stores
session data internally. No need to extract, validate, or back up tokens. Just reuse the
same browser profile directory. All the token management code became dead weight.

Struggles:
- Session state kept getting overwritten with invalid data on auth failures
- Repeated failures needed exponential backoff
- Windows-specific encoding issues with output capture

This was the 'make it work reliably' phase before the bigger architectural rewrite.
